---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { breadcrumbStructuredData } from "../lib/faq-data.js";
---

<Layout
  title="About — ZzzCalc"
  description="About ZzzCalc, a free sleep cycle calculator built on 90-minute REM cycle science. No ads, no tracking, no accounts. Just better mornings."
  canonical="https://zzzcalc.vercel.app/about"
  structuredData={[
    breadcrumbStructuredData([
      { name: "Home", url: "https://zzzcalc.vercel.app" },
      { name: "About", url: "https://zzzcalc.vercel.app/about" },
    ]),
  ]}
>
  <section class="pt-28 pb-16 sm:pt-40 sm:pb-24">
    <div class="container-main">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h1 class="font-serif text-2xl sm:text-3xl lg:text-4xl tracking-tight mb-6" style="color: var(--text-page);">About ZzzCalc</h1>

        <div class="space-y-5 text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--text-card-muted);">
          <p>
            ZzzCalc was built to solve a single problem: most people wake up groggy because their alarm fires mid-cycle, and the existing tools to fix this are cluttered with ads, tracking, and unnecessary friction.
          </p>

          <p>
            The 90-minute sleep cycle model has been understood since Kleitman and Dement's foundational EEG research in 1953. Despite decades of sleep science, most alarm clocks and sleep calculators still treat sleep as a single block of time rather than a series of repeating cycles. ZzzCalc applies the cycle math directly — forward and backward — so you can pick a bedtime or wake time that lands at a cycle boundary, not in the middle of deep sleep.
          </p>

          <p>
            The tool is designed to be local-first and private by default. Every calculation runs in your browser. Your settings are saved to localStorage, not to a server. There are no accounts, no email sign-ups, and no personally identifiable data collection. We use Google Analytics to understand aggregate usage patterns — no cross-site tracking, no ad targeting.</p>
            <p class="mt-3">Upon first visit, a consent banner lets you choose between standard analytics or anonymized tracking. You can also opt out at any time by installing the <a href="https://tools.google.com/dlpage/gaoptout" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Google Analytics opt-out browser add-on</a> or enabling Do Not Track in your browser.</p>

          <h2 class="font-serif text-lg sm:text-xl tracking-tight mt-8 mb-3" style="color: var(--text-card);">What makes ZzzCalc different</h2>

          <ul class="space-y-2 list-disc pl-5">
            <li><strong style="color: var(--text-card);">No ads.</strong> Not "fewer ads" — zero ads. The page loads fast and stays clean.</li>
            <li><strong style="color: var(--text-card);">No tracking.</strong> No cross-site tracking, no fingerprinting, no ad profiling. We use anonymized aggregate analytics only. Your sleep preferences stay on your device.</li>
            <li><strong style="color: var(--text-card);">No accounts.</strong> There is nothing to sign up for. Open the page, use the calculator, close it.</li>
            <li><strong style="color: var(--text-card);">Visual timeline.</strong> See exactly when your alarm will fire relative to each sleep stage.</li>
            <li><strong style="color: var(--text-card);">Adjustable latency.</strong> The default 14 minutes matches the population average, but you can set it anywhere from 5 to 45 minutes.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2 class="font-serif text-lg sm:text-xl tracking-tight mt-8 mb-3" style="color: var(--text-card);">The calculation</h2>

          <p>
            ZzzCalc uses the standard 90-minute sleep cycle formula. In wake-up mode, it subtracts your chosen number of cycles (plus your sleep latency) from your target wake time. In bedtime mode, it adds your latency plus cycles to your bedtime. The result is a set of times that align with natural cycle boundaries — no rounding to 15-minute blocks, no assumptions about your schedule.
          </p>

          <p>
            The 90-minute cycle is an average, not a rule. Individual cycles range from 70 to 110 minutes, and your personal ideal may differ. The calculator is a scheduling heuristic, not a medical instrument.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
